      <div type="translation">
        <p> … a monastery with a pavillon, with a shrine (hall), … with a garden as the giving away as pious gift … At the border to <foreign>…nigala</foreign> a reed cluster (<foreign>vetrakula</foreign>) … a field, sixteen (*<foreign>nivartana</foreign>s). At the border to Pāpikala … <foreign>nivartana</foreign>s and … given by the king in the district Maccha… At the border to <foreign>…paḍa</foreign> thirty-two <foreign>nivartana</foreign>s, (given by the) king. At the border to ?[ra]pura twenty-four <foreign>nivartana</foreign>s.</p>
        <p>Of …ḍala five hundred cows, four-poled (<foreign>caturyaṣṭi</foreign>) bullock … carts, as servants (<foreign>preṣyarūpa</foreign>) twenty-four female and male slaves, four jar-shaped cauldrons (<foreign>kumbhikaṭāha</foreign>), two iron cauldrons, four brass vessels (<foreign>bhājana</foreign>), a eddy-shaped (? <foreign>abhikāra</foreign>) bowl and “Greek” lamps, a tank behind the Antaragiri, and one thousand old Kāhāpanas as permanent endowment. This is the Great Talavara’s giving away as pious gift. In Atapa, at the northern side, fifty-two (?) <foreign>nivartana</foreign>s. This (of the Great Talavara) together with his wife, sons, and grand-sons. To the <foreign>nikāya</foreign> of the noble Puvvaseliyas.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <p n="17">
          <note>Compare the end of Dharanikota pillar inscription (EIAD <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00407.xml">407</ref>), ll. 7–9: <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">bhikhusaghasa puvasel<name>i</name>yāna nigāyasa parigahe dhama<unclear>ca</unclear>kadhayo paḍiṭhapito savalokasatvahitasukhāya</foreign>.</note>
        </p>
